# Fluff Date: 2026-02-28 11:02:26
<overview>
<p>The Zugvogel is a two-hundred-ton Omni support aircraft developed by Lockheed/CBM on Gibbs for the Lyran Commonwealth. Conceived during the post-Jihad reconstruction era to replace a bewildering array of modified King Karnov transports, the Zugvogel leverages OmniPod technology to fill nearly any support role from a single airframe. Where the LCAF Quartermaster Corps once required extensive factory retooling to produce specialized King Karnov variants, the Zugvogel can be reconfigured in the field through modular pod swaps. Its enormous pod capacity of over seventy tons allows it to mount weapons, sensors, medical facilities, or cargo space in virtually any combination, following the same consolidation philosophy that led to the Morgenstern OmniFighter.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>Powered by an Edasich commercial-grade fusion engine, the Zugvogel is approximately twenty-five percent faster than the King Karnov it was designed to replace, with a cruising speed sufficient to keep pace with most ground offensives. Eleven and a half tons of military-grade armor rated at BAR 10 provides respectable protection for a support aircraft, while CASE reinforcement protects the crew and airframe against catastrophic ammunition detonation in armed configurations. An advanced fire control system enhances weapons accuracy across all configurations that carry offensive armament.</p><p>The aircraft's defining characteristic is its seventy-one and a half tons of available pod space. Five factory-produced OmniPod kits cover the most common mission profiles. The Prime configuration serves as a heavily armed combat transport, pairing forward-mounted missile launchers and light autocannons with a rear-facing light Gauss rifle and over twenty-three tons of cargo space. The A configuration transforms the aircraft into a flying command post packed with sensor suites and a C3 master computer capable of coordinating an entire planetary campaign. The B and C configurations fill medical and repair roles respectively, mounting a ten-theater MASH unit and mobile field repair bases. The D configuration, nicknamed the Raubvogel, serves as an aerial gunship mounting twin Gauss rifles and a heavy PPC capable of threatening heavy aerospace fighters.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>The B configuration transforms the Zugvogel into a flying field hospital. A ten-theater MASH unit provides surgical capability for mass casualty events, supported by paramedic equipment and a field kitchen for extended operations. A fifty-ton vehicle bay accommodates rescue vehicles and ambulances, while a small infantry bay can transport medical personnel. Powerful searchlights illuminate the landing zone when the aircraft is grounded for treatment operations.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>The LCAF and later the LAAF have long maintained one of the largest fixed-wing support aircraft fleets in the Inner Sphere. Lockheed/CBM's KC-9 King Karnov became a mainstay of Lyran logistic units following its debut in 3001, with the Quartermaster Corps requesting numerous modifications to the transport's spacious cargo bay over the decades. Gunship, bomber, mobile command post, and MASH conversions all saw limited production runs, but each required expensive factory retooling and dedicated manufacturing lines.</p><p>By the late Jihad era, Lockheed/CBM sought to address this inefficiency. Drawing inspiration from the success of their Morgenstern OmniFighter, which had replaced three separate aerospace fighter designs with a single modular airframe, the company applied OmniPod construction to the support aircraft role. The Zugvogel entered production on Gibbs in the early 3080s, with the plant having escaped the damage that crippled Lockheed/CBM facilities on Donegal and Tharkad during the Jihad.</p><p>The aircraft was still completing final quartermaster trials when it began attracting attention from multiple armed forces. The Third Skye CMR, a paratrooper-trained combat unit, was among the first to put the Zugvogel through operational testing during a series of RAF-LCAF war games. Using the mobile command post configuration to coordinate command and control while relying on the primary configuration for rapid paratrooper deployment, the regiment reportedly forced an entire combined arms battalion to surrender through a combination of aerial fire support and hit-and-run infantry tactics.</p><p>The Lyran Quartermaster Corps planned to requisition at least two hundred Zugvogels over the following five years, and interest extended beyond Lyran borders. The Republic of the Sphere and several other nations made inquiries about possible purchases once field trials concluded, suggesting the design may see broader adoption across the Inner Sphere.</p>
</history>

